content: The World Health Organization recommends that adults aged 65 years and above should do at least 150–300 minutes of moderate-intensity aerobic physical activity, or at least 75–150 minutes of vigorous-intensity aerobic physical activity, throughout the week. They should also do muscle-strengthening activities at moderate or greater intensity that involve all major muscle groups on 2 or more days a week, as these provide additional health benefits. Older adults with limited mobility should do physical activity to enhance balance and prevent falls on 3 or more days a week.

Balance training is crucial for older adults. The American College of Sports Medicine (ACSM) recommends balance exercises 2-3 days per week for fall prevention. These exercises should challenge postural control and may include standing on one leg, heel-to-toe walking, and yoga or tai chi. Falls are the leading cause of injury-related death among adults 65 and older, making balance training a critical component of any exercise program for this age group.
sourceTitle: ACSM Exercise Guidelines for Older Adults

content: For strength training in older adults, ACSM recommends 2-3 days per week of resistance exercises involving major muscle groups. Start with 1 set of 10-15 repetitions at moderate intensity (60-70% of 1-repetition maximum). Progress gradually by increasing sets, repetitions, or resistance. Proper form is essential to prevent injury. Rest at least 48 hours between sessions targeting the same muscle groups to allow for recovery.

Contraindications and exercise modifications: For individuals with knee osteoarthritis, avoid high-impact activities and deep squatting. Focus on strengthening quadriceps and hamstrings with low-impact exercises. For those with balance issues, perform exercises near a wall or sturdy chair for support. Anyone experiencing dizziness, chest pain, or unusual shortness of breath during exercise should stop immediately and consult a healthcare provider.

Progression principles for older adults: Increase exercise volume gradually - no more than 10% increase per week in duration, frequency, or intensity. Monitor for signs of overtraining including persistent fatigue, decreased performance, or increased injury rate. Regression is appropriate when form breaks down, pain occurs, or the individual cannot complete the prescribed repetitions. The goal is sustainable, long-term fitness, not rapid gains.
sourceTitle: US Physical Activity Guidelines - Older Adults
